===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{phonetics}} A complex [[vowel]] [[sound]] that begins with the sound of one vowel and ends with the sound of another vowel, in the same [[syllable]].
#: For example: "ae", "au", "ou"
# {{rare}} A vowel [[digraph]] or [[ligature]].
#* '''1854''', Robert Bigsby, ''Historical and Topographical Description of Repton, in the County of Derby'', Woodfall and Kinder, [http://books.google.com/books?id=68oHAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA47&dq=diphthong page 47]:
#*: And he might have written the name, also, with the '''diphthong''' æ, as well as the single vowel, in the initial syllable, throughout all the preceding forms.
#* '''1860''', Joseph E. Worcester, ''An Elementary Dictionary of the English Language'', A New Edition, Swan, Brewer, and Tileston (publishers), [http://books.google.com/books?id=CuIzKfd61ZcC&pg=PA12&dq=diphthong page 12]:
#*: An improper '''diphthong''' has only one of the vowels sounded; as, ''ea'' in ''heat'', ''oa'' in ''coal''.
#* '''1874''', Theophilus Dwight Hall, ''A Child’s First Latin Book'', John Murray (publisher), [http://books.google.com/books?id=rsMDAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA3&dq=diphthong page 3]:
#*: The '''diphthong''' ''ae'' is sounded like ''ē'' (§7); that is, it has the sound of ''ey'' in ''they''.

